# Information, pooled

With our current toolset (linear regression), there are two avenues for us with respect to how we analyse clustered data. We can either ignore the clustering completely (and violate our assumptions), we can add the cluster-level differences in as another predictor. These reflect different ways in which we can "pool" information from across the different clusters.  

:::sticky
__Complete Pooling__  

All information from different clusters is pooled together to estimate the relevant association.  


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
lm(grade ~ motiv, data = schoolmot)
```
:::

Take all the children, fit a regression line for `grade ~ motivation`.  

:::

:::sticky
__No Pooling__  

Information from each cluster contributes **only** to that specific cluster's estimate.  


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
lm(grade ~ motiv*schoolid, data = schoolmot)
```
:::

Estimate school-specific differences in grades, and school-specific differences in the effect of motivation on grades. Get _loads_ of coefficients that aren't really of interest.   



:::


Estimating the school-specific differences in our model (the no-pooling approach) is clearly better than simply ignoring them, but it does mean that we are treating the schools as if they are completely independent entities.  
Suppose we had another school - School X - for which we had only _three_ children's data (@fig-borrowstrength). Intuitively, we don't want to trust the line for School X as much as we trust the others (where we have 30 children's data). 


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![Blue lines show the estimated fitted values from the no-pooling approach lm(grade ~ motiv * schoolid). School X's estimate is based on just the 3 datapoints from that school, and does not take into account any of the other schools in anyway.](01a_clustered_files/figure-html/fig-borrowstrength-1.png){#fig-borrowstrength fig-align='center' width=80%}
